> I hear the troubled motors constant whine and the smell grim odor of gasoline. Oil washes the street like water before my feet. I stand here gazing into the future, existing in the present, remembering the past, my life but one turn of the cogwheel’s many. <br>
        On the distant horizon the sky is bleak, bright blueness of the sky fades to a dull brown gray. The exhaust of cars and factories drives upward seeking higher and higher with mounting density. The gloom encroaches the once novel city warmed by the rays of beaming sun. Now the relentless hum of neon lights like the murmur of the endless motors fills my inner ear. As I gaze down the blackened city streets I am bathed in artificial lights endless yellow stream.<br>
        To what extent has my life become like the motors and the lights? To what extent has my blood become like oil and my heart like steel? Are the machines I build the manifestation of myself or the heralds of my doom? Each day I move with a routine that is so constant and dull I could keep time with it. Each day I drive the fan belt and breathe the warm dank air that it circulates. My hands are so deeply worn and burned from the many hours at the forge that their prints, their very identity, has worn off, lost amidst the churning and boiling of molten metal. <br>
        I have little care for the earth as I push one lifeless steel bar after another into the fiery forge. I care not about the mines that strip the earth of its very blood so that I may control it and form it into that which cannot give life. Am I a god that sucks blood from the veins of earth turning it into something dull and life less? Does this make me a god of death? What sort are my machines that run not on red blood, that which is the color of the heart, but black blood, that which is the color of coal and soot. Their sharp jagged teeth furthering my purpose as they rip the earths skin and mold  it to the images of my mind. <br>
The routine has so dulled my senses and my feelings that my heart is no more than the steel it forges. I have become what I create, something that is lifeless. I bring a plague of so artificial a nature that nature itself recoils in terror. <br>
        Once I existed with care, when I was young. I would play amidst the jays and larks, flying with the butterfly, drinking with the hummingbird. The yellow sun gave me strength and vigor. Each day in the sandbox I fantasized of knights and kings of princes and paupers, of the very things which a child’s heart yearns for and that the mind creates. I remember the cheer of my friends when I caught the winning touch down at the high school game and the calm soothing voice of Sally Lane as we sat cuddling in front of the high movie screen. Even in college days did I still fantasize and take the world as it came to me. Drinking with my friends, studying now and then, experimenting and enjoying life. It was not until I was cast out of the cast that had so far been my security that which was my friend and family that I realized what the world was. I moved away from the quite town of Orange Ville to Urbane Metropolis. <br>
        Now the toxic tar that filtrates the air I draw up into my lungs; the venting sewers my incense. Even the perfume of a women seems to resemble only fine motor oil. My face is no longer clean as it once was, but is greased with the labor of the world. Why is it I have come to forge the machines, why is it that I have come to have a heart of steel. Has my blood really turned black, have my eyes really grown accustomed to the artificial yellow that I know now as sun? How much longer will my life continue to progress with the monotonous revolution of the cog wheel? Is the plight of man to be the harbinger of doom, the crafter of machines? How many machines have I crafted and how many do I have yet to craft. And yet, I’ve never stepped foot inside a factory.<br>
<br>
-Falc <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ufalcondelta.showPublicProfile?language=EN>FalconDelta</A> at: 2/25/02 8:51:26 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ubutterflyparadox.showPublicProfile?language=EN>butterflyparadox</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://liquid2k.com/blueparadox/moon.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/26/02 6:49:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=524.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> story</span><hr size=1> Thats a very intense story falcon.  I love how you've compared the machines with the human...its like routine made him lose his individuality...its really interesting how you have the machines personified, but the man is dehumanised....it's like there is a confusion between he two...who is more important, and who is more needed?<br>
